<P>
YOLO SHERIFF ROD GRAHAM INDICTED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SACRAMENTO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A federal grand jury indicted Yolo County Sheriff Rod Graham today for 
conspiracy, extortion and bribery stemming from a three-year FBI investigation 
into corruption in the California Legislature. 
</P>
<P>
It was the second indictment involving the sheriff's office. Last month, 
Graham's former assistant, Wendell Luttrull, also was charged with extorting 
money in exchange for official services. Luttrull pleaded guilty Dec. 1 to a 
single count of violating the federal Hobbs Act. At the time, Luttrull made a 
court statement implicating his former boss. If he is convicted, the charges 
against Graham could bring a maximum sentence of 75 years in prison. He will 
not be arrested, but ordered to appear in court later. 
</P>
