IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
HOME MORTGAGE RATES INCREASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fixed-rate mortgage rates rose 0.03 percentage points this week and 
adjustable-rate deals were up by 0.04 percentage points, the Federal Home Loan 
Mortgage Corp. said today. 
</P>
<P>
The agency, which buys mortgages from lenders and packages them as securities 
for sale to investors, said interest on fixed-rate loans increased to 10.80% 
this week, up from 10.77% last week. Adjustable-rate mortgages averaged 8.53%, 
up from 8.49% from last week. 
</P>
<P>
The fixed-rate average is for a 30-year loan covering 80% of a home's cost. The 
adjustable-rate average also is for 30 years but for 75% of the home price. 
</P>
</TEXT>
